The murder rates vary quite a bit. The minimum murder rate, of .5 per 100,000, is Hawaii, while DC is the max at 16.5 per 100,00. The rates also vary across regions. When looking at the entire murder rate of the US:

us_murder_rate <- murders %>% 
  summarize( murder_rate= sum(total) / sum(population) * 100000) %>%
  .$murder_rate

us_murder_rate
## [1] 3.034555

Compared to the murder rates across entire regions:

murders %>% 
  group_by(region) %>%
  summarize(avg_murder_rate= mean(sum(total) / sum(population) * 100000))
## # A tibble: 4 x 2
##          region avg_murder_rate
##          <fctr>           <dbl>
## 1     Northeast        2.655592
## 2         South        3.626558
## 3 North Central        2.731334
## 4          West        2.656175

Yet, lets also look at the means for region murder rates when weighing each state equally (rather than total murders and populations of regions):

murders %>% 
  group_by(region) %>%
  summarize(avg_of_murder_rates= mean(murder_rate), variance=var(murder_rate))
## # A tibble: 4 x 3
##          region avg_of_murder_rates  variance
##          <fctr>               <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1     Northeast            1.847500  1.378477
## 2         South            4.417012 11.376348
## 3 North Central            2.182040  2.069729
## 4          West            1.833401  1.373954

It is evident that there is definitely an increase in murders in the South compared to the rest of the country. Once you dive into the South though, you can see that the variance is very high for the different murder rates across states in that region. Looking at the summarized data for the south, there are 5 states (West Virginia, Kentucky, Alabama, Oklahoma and North Carolina) that have murder rates below the national average. However, from the boxplot of murder rates in the south, the two upper outliers (LA and DC) are pulling up the average quite a bit.

Even though the West has the lowest average murder rates (when weighing each state equally), Nevada, New Mexico, California and Arizona all have murder rates above the US murder rate.

Comparing variance with the entire country:

var(murders$murder_rate)
## [1] 6.032518

We can further evaluate by making histograms and box plots of murder rates for the entire country, and then by region:

NC <-murders$region=="North Central"
W <-murders$region=="West"
S <-murders$region=="South"
NE <-murders$region=="Northeast"


hist(murders$murder_rate, col= "purple", density = 45, main = "Distribution of Murder Rates in the US", xlab = "Murder Rates", ylab="Number of states within each murder rate range")

hist(murders$murder_rate[NC], col= "green", density = 45, main = "Murder Rates in the North Central Region", xlab = "Murder Rates", ylab="Number of states within each murder rate range")

hist(murders$murder_rate[W], col= "blue", density = 45, main = "Murder Rates in the Western Region", xlab = "Murder Rates", ylab="Number of states within each murder rate range")

hist(murders$murder_rate[S], breaks=10, col= "pink", main = "Murder Rates in the Southern Region", xlim=c(0,17), xlab = "Murder Rates", ylab="Number of states within each murder rate range")

hist(murders$murder_rate[NE], col= "red", density = 45, main = "Murder Rates in the Northeastern Region", xlab = "Murder Rates", ylab="Number of states within each murder rate range")

boxplot(murders$murder_rate, main = "Distribution of all murder rates")

boxplot(murders$murder_rate[NC], main = "Distribution of North Central murder rates")

boxplot(murders$murder_rate[NE],main = "Distribution of Northeast murder rates")

boxplot(murders$murder_rate[S], main = "Distribution of South murder rates")

boxplot(murders$murder_rate[W], main = "Distribution of West murder rates")

Based on the histogram for the entire country, most states have a murder rates between 2-4; and about 20 states have a murder rate between 0-2. There is definitely variance among the regions, and while the south has the highest murder rate, it certainly has two upper outliers that slightly skew the regions data. Yet, it does only have one state with a murder rate between 0-1; although most southern states fall between 2-4. As noted above, the West has the lowest murder rate, but there is a huge gap between the regions safest states and its most dangerous states; so one cannot assume that every state in the West is below the national average for murders. The Northeastern states are pretty evenly distributed. The North Central states have a couple upper murder rates between 4 and 6, but most states are below 3.

  1. Write a report for your friends reminding them that the US is a large and diverse country with 50 very different states as well as the District of Columbia (DC). Suppose one of your friends loves hiking, one wants to live in a warm climate, and another would like to be close to several large cosmopolitan cities. Recommend a desirable state for each friend.

Chosing a place to live in the United States

While the U.S. murder rate can be a bit concerning when comparing to other countries, just remember that the U.S. is a very large country, and there are many safe places to live! Looking at the information above, while the South has the highest murder rates in the country, there are still many safe and wonderful places to live there! Additionally, while the West has the lowest in the country, its still best to examine the information before picking a state from that region at random.

Above, Ive calculated the murder rates for the each state in the United States, and compared them across the entire country and by region. 20 states in the U.S. have a murder rate less than 2; and the safest state, Vermont, has a murder rate less than Belgium, Portugal, Ireland, Italy, and Canada. While the second safest state, New Hampshire, is less than Canada and Portugal.

Best Place to live for hiking

If hiking and outdoors are the main interest, the West is likely where you want to live! Based on that, I would recommend the following states for their wonderful hiking (and safety!):

  • Hawaii (murder rate of 0.51)
  • Idaho (murder rate of 0.77)

I listed two here depending on the type of weather you enjoy. Hawaii is great for hiking year round, but Idaho has great hiking in the summer, and skiing in the winter!

Hawaii

Idaho

This website has the best hikes in the U.S., yet it really depends on the type of hiking and weather you enjoy.

Best place to live for a warm climate

If you would like to live in a warm climate, I recommend the South. Despite its high murder rate, there are many great places to live there! DC and Louisiana both have murder rates that are outliers for the region, and are a big reason why the murder rate in the South is so high! If you look at the box plot and histograms for the South above, you can see the large variance in the rates among those states.

Depending where in the South you are, the climate can change pretty drastically. While West Virginia has the lowest murder rate, it gets a lot colder than other states.

In this case, I would recommend Alabama or Kentucky. Both states have warm climates (Alabama is a little warmer), and are the safer of the southern states.

However, if moving away from the south, I would again suggest Hawaii! It has a wonderful climate and is incredibly safe.

Alabama

Kentucky

Best place to live with city access

If being close to several metropolitian areas is the main focus, the Northeast is your best option! There are many cities very close together, and each one is unique and great in its own way (even the dangerous city of DC).

While Vermont and New Hampshire are the safest cities in this region, the are not that close to the major cities. Looking at a map of the Northeast, I would actually recommend New York! Its not the safest one list, but its below the national average and incredibly convenient if you want to hop between cities on the East coast!

Map of Northeast

In general, living closer to cosmopolitan cities is likely to have higher murder rates in general, but living in the state of New York, and not directly in NYC will offer an incredibly safe and great place to live!

New York City
